> can we use the devnet tokens in the realworld final deployment of the app as well?\
  No, Devnet tokens cannot be used in the real-world final deployment.\
  Here is why:\
\
  ### 1. The Networks are Completely Isolated\
  Devnet and Mainnet are two entirely separate databases.\
\
  \'95 Devnet is a sandbox designed only for testing. Anyone can generate unlimited Devnet SOL for free. Because of this, Devnet\
  tokens have zero monetary value.\
  \'95 Mainnet is the real-world Solana blockchain. It has strict economic rules, and real SOL must be bought from exchanges\
  (like Coinbase or Binance) using real money.\
  If you try to use a Devnet wallet or Devnet tokens on Mainnet, the production network will reject the transaction because\
  those tokens do not exist on the real blockchain.\
\
  ### 2. Transitioning to the Real World (Mainnet)\
\
  When you are ready to launch the app to the public:\
  1. Switch the Network config: We will change the RPC URL in the client and daemon code from  https://api.devnet.solana.com\
  (Devnet) to  https://api.mainnet-beta.solana.com  (Mainnet).\
  2. Deploy on Mainnet: We will deploy the smart contract to Mainnet (which will cost a one-time fee of real SOL for the rent\
  storage).\
  3. Fund with Real SOL: RBN operators will fund their wallets with a very small amount of real SOL to pay for transaction\
  fees.\
      \'95 Note: Because Solana fees are extremely cheap (typically less than $0.0002 per transaction), funding a node with just\
      $1 worth of real SOL is enough to keep it registering on-chain for years.\
\
